ving the placeholder; it seems like the right call is to keep it for now. However, there’s this status that includes metadata related to `org.springframework/spring-webmvc/5.3.18`, which might indicate an untracked directory with generated metadata. I need to think through how this affects our overall setup and whether we’ll actually need that metadata or if it can be safely ignored. It feels a bit confusing, but I want to ensure everything stays organized!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented focused coverage for `ResourceBundleViewResolver`.\n\nAdded:\n\n- `tests/src/org.springframework/spring-webmvc/5.3.18/src/test/java/org_springframework/spring_webmvc/ResourceBundleViewResolverTest.java`\n  - Public dedicated test class for the active dynamic-access class.\n  - Exercises `ResourceBundleViewResolver.resolveViewName(...)` through normal public API.\n  - Reaches `ResourceBundle.getBundle(String, Locale, ClassLoader)` via the resolver’s resource-bundle loading path.\n  - Verifies the resolved `InternalResourceView` and configured URL.\n\n- `tests/src/org.springframework/spring-webmvc/5.3.18/src/test/resources/org_springframework/spring_webmvc/resource_bundle_views.properties`\n  - Classpath resource bundle used by the resolver.\n\nI did not run tests, per instruction. Note: `git status` also shows an unrelated untracked `metadata/org.springframework/spring-webmvc/5.3.18/` directory that I did not modify.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_03c95e5e1db1cf34016a264b34d03481959f6a1ef65f2f9845\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 405, "output": 728, "cacheRead": 23040, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 24173, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1780894499723, "responseId": "resp_03c95e5e1db1cf34016a264b2448508195b55cc0686ebe50a5"}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Checking metadata and deprecation warnings**\n\nI see that there's untracked metadata, and it seems we shouldn’t edit it. It could be preexisting, probably created by the environment, and we might not need to include it. There's also a concern about test classes needing to be public, but that’s not directly our issue. I should check if any deprecation warnings arise from the ResourceBundleViewResolver, as compiling with -Werror could cause failures. Existing tests do not show deprecation issues, so that's a relief.\n\n**Addressing warnings and context issues**\n\nI’m considering adding `@SuppressWarnings(\"deprecation\")` to keep the code clean but need to see if that warning matters. There might be some potential issues with the `GenericWebApplicationContext` import. It’s essential to review when `applicationContext.close` occurs, especially regarding the child context when exceptions happen. I should look at the `ResourceBundleViewResolver#getBundle` method to resolve correctly. I wonder if certain calls like `setBundleClassLoader` and bean registration are genuinely necessary. Lastly, it seems I may not need a Spring tests dependency for `MockServletContext`.\n\n**Considering placeholder removal**\n\nI’m unsure about removing the placeholder; it seems like the right call is to keep it for now. However, there’s this status that includes metadata related to `org.springframework/spring-webmvc/5.3.18`, which might indicate an untracked directory with generated metadata. I need to think through how this affects our overall setup and whether we’ll actually need that metadata or if it can be safely ignored. It feels a bit confusing, but I want to ensure everything stays organized!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_03c95e5e1db1cf34016a264b24f0dc8195a860b5d27ccb51d1\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJks0-IT1vYwfitoiovMJ0oGnt